## 12. Authentication and Authorization Model

This is one of the most important parts of the design.

## 12.1 Between browser and app backend

Use the existing application auth model:

- Firebase Auth for identity
- admin role resolution via Firestore roles/admin model

Only admin users should access the document-generation controls.

## 12.2 Between app backend and OpenAI

Use a server-side `OPENAI_API_KEY` in your backend environment.

The key must remain server-side only.

## 12.3 Between OpenAI and your MCP server

The recommended pattern is **OAuth**, with **dynamic client registration** supported where appropriate.

### Why

- aligns with OpenAI’s recommended MCP auth pattern
- avoids brittle shared-secret-only setups for long-term use
- supports safer workspace and user-level authorization flows if you also connect the server in ChatGPT

## 12.4 First-phase acceptable fallback

For an initial internal-only application integration, you can start with a simpler server authentication pattern if needed, such as:

- network restrictions
- signed internal headers
- application-to-MCP shared secret

But this should be treated as a stepping stone, not the final security model.

