## 21. Security and Safety Model

This is where adults earn their pay.

## 21.1 Core risks

| Risk | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| prompt injection | malicious reference content could influence model behavior |
| over-broad tool access | model could call tools outside the intended workflow |
| sensitive data leakage | too much context may be sent to the model or MCP |
| unsafe write actions | model-triggered writes can damage data |
| untrusted MCP servers | third-party or proxy servers can exfiltrate data |

## 21.2 Safety rules for this application

### 1. Start read-heavy and write-light
The MCP server should begin primarily as a read/retrieval and structured-assistance server.

### 2. Avoid direct data writes from model tool calls
At least in the first implementation phase, the model should not directly write to Firestore through MCP tools.

### 3. Keep admin review mandatory
Generated content must be reviewed before publishing.

### 4. Restrict tool access per workflow
Never expose the full toolset if only two tools are needed.

### 5. Do not pass unnecessary sensitive data
Only send the minimum needed context.

### 6. Use trusted servers only
Your own MCP server should be the trusted endpoint. Do not route the app through unofficial third-party proxy MCP servers just because they have a cute README.

