## 30. Final Operating Model

When implemented correctly, ChatGPT via MCP should operate in this web application as follows:

- the **admin user** starts a document-generation workflow in the web app
- the **app backend** validates the request, creates a job, and calls the OpenAI Responses API
- the **model** uses the configured **remote MCP server** to retrieve templates, business context, and supporting references
- the **MCP server** returns controlled, scoped data to support generation
- the **model** produces a structured draft or metadata output
- the **application** stores the output in Firestore as a draft version
- the **admin** reviews, edits, and approves the result
- the **application** saves the approved output to the final document record
- **audit logs and operational logs** record what happened

That is the intended operating model.

ChatGPT via MCP is not supposed to be a novelty feature bolted onto the side of the platform. It is supposed to be a governed, admin-facing document-generation subsystem that works alongside your existing Firebase, Firestore, Cloudflare, and Gemini layers.

